00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:26.420
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
So today, we're

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:30.960
going to get into innovation
at the institutional level.

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:34.100
So that's our fundamental topic.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:35.730
Because we've been
out for two weeks,

00:00:35.730 --> 00:00:39.950
let me do a recap so that we're
all current with the underlying

00:00:39.950 --> 00:00:41.210
framework.

00:00:41.210 --> 00:00:44.150
Class 1, we talked about, as
you remember, growth theory,

00:00:44.150 --> 00:00:47.030
and we read Robert Solow
and Solow taught us

00:00:47.030 --> 00:00:49.760
that technological and
related innovation is

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:54.170
the dominant causative
factor in economic growth.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:57.230
Old classical economics posited
that it was capital supplier

00:00:57.230 --> 00:00:58.280
labor supply.

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:00.830
Those remain important, but
the monster in the room,

00:01:00.830 --> 00:01:05.030
Solow found, to the
tune of 60% or more,

00:01:05.030 --> 00:01:08.120
is technological and
related innovation.

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:10.100
We also read Paul Romer.

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:14.810
And Paul Romer
says, wait a minute.

00:01:14.810 --> 00:01:16.790
It's not just having
an R&D system.

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:19.010
You've got to staff
that R&D system.

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:20.870
It's the talent base.

00:01:20.870 --> 00:01:22.910
That's a key driver.

00:01:22.910 --> 00:01:26.040
That's another critical factor.

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:31.473
So his phrase is quote, "human
capital engaged in research."

00:01:31.473 --> 00:01:33.890
So if you train great physicists
and they're driving cabs,

00:01:33.890 --> 00:01:35.870
they're not engaged
in research, right?

00:01:35.870 --> 00:01:38.580
That's a no-net gain.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:42.420
But if they're engaged in that
system, that's what's critical.

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:46.980
And his prospector
theory says the size

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:50.830
of a well-qualified talent
base makes a huge difference.

00:01:50.830 --> 00:01:54.120
That's a key driver.

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:56.390
Talent on task and a
lot of talent on task

00:01:56.390 --> 00:01:59.010
is better than less
talent on task.

00:01:59.010 --> 00:02:02.760
So those are two fundamental
innovation factors

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:05.520
that we arrived at
in the first class.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:07.530
Class number 2,
we began thinking

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:10.025
about innovation systems.

00:02:10.025 --> 00:02:11.900
So we got two factors
out of the first class.

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:14.750
Then we began to
think about systems.

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:18.290
Nelson tells us that there are
national systems of innovation

00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:22.780
that you can analyze,
innovation at the systems level,

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:25.957
and look at the
actors in that system

00:02:25.957 --> 00:02:27.790
and the strength of the
actors and therefore

00:02:27.790 --> 00:02:31.040
the strength of
the whole system.

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:36.340
So that gives us a
third innovation factor,

00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:37.390
which is really--

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:41.320
we'll call it
innovation organization.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:43.170
And then we read some
other pieces in there.

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:45.610
I'll highlight a couple.

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:48.760
Don Kash and Robert
Rycroft said, you've

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:49.960
got to network the actors.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:55.760
It's the network, the strength
of the network of the actors,

00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:58.730
that's now, particularly
in a 21st century context,

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:01.340
particularly critical.

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:05.845
And we also read Charles
Schulze, a noted economist

00:03:05.845 --> 00:03:07.220
from the University
of Minnesota,

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:11.120
who was a senior governmental
official in the Lyndon Johnson

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:13.370
era and then Jimmy Carter era.

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:18.290
And he raises the issue
of what's the public role?

00:03:18.290 --> 00:03:22.010
What's the private role as we
look at innovation systems?

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:23.900
What should the public
function be versus

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:26.390
what the private
sector should be.

00:03:26.390 --> 00:03:30.310
An absolutely fundamental
set of issues.

00:03:30.310 --> 00:03:32.500
So then we did classes 3 and 4.

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:35.140
We essentially focused on
the innovation challenge

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:37.360
ahead in production.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:40.340
And in class 3, we looked
at the kind of history

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:44.270
of US manufacturing problems.

00:03:44.270 --> 00:03:47.690
We read Kent Hughes,
and he explains

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:50.450
the fascinating competition
when Japan launches

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:54.350
a brilliant new innovation
system and production

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:56.420
around quality.

00:03:56.420 --> 00:03:58.340
That's where the
rust belt begins.

00:03:58.340 --> 00:04:03.320
That's where US statistics
about growing inequality begin.

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:06.920
That's where this problem
that we're now worse off at,

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:08.510
that's where it commences.

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:10.610
And then we looked
at Korea and Japan

00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:14.360
and how they built
manufacturing-led innovation

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.290
systems.

00:04:16.290 --> 00:04:21.029
And then in class 4, we looked
at the current US manufacturing

00:04:21.029 --> 00:04:21.540
problems.

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:25.590
So I wanted to put a set
of real issues, really

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:29.190
timely critical issues, kind
of on the table, if you will,

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:32.930
at the very beginning of the
class so that we're not--

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.020
you know, this is not a
class about abstraction.

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:37.800
These are real issues
that are extremely

00:04:37.800 --> 00:04:41.700
timely in the way in which
society operates and functions.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:46.440
And the US built a
comparative advantage

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:49.020
around its R&D system.

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:52.860
It did not organize around
manufacturing-led innovation

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:58.350
like Japan, Germany, Korea,
Taiwan, China, and so on.

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:01.890
We missed that
organizational step,

00:05:01.890 --> 00:05:06.850
and we are continuing
to pay a price for that.

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:10.680
So we talked some two weeks
ago about David Autor and some

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:13.020
of his absolutely
fascinating work

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:18.300
on the decline of
US manufacturing

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:20.400
and the effect on
the labor force.

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:22.260
He has a new piece
out that talks

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:35.410
about the effect on innovation
of the intense competition

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:35.910
with China.

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:37.980
And essentially,
what he finds is

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:41.310
that firms that go up against
head-on-head competition

00:05:41.310 --> 00:05:44.190
over a particular
product line with China

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:47.910
have to slash their innovation
capability, their R&D

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:51.180
capability, in order
to stay in the game.

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:53.520
But that kills them long term.

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:57.090
So that this
competition with Japan

00:05:57.090 --> 00:06:00.155
is not only having an
effect on the labor market,

00:06:00.155 --> 00:06:02.280
but it's also having a big
effect on the innovation

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:04.380
capability of companies.

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:08.960
And then we talked about
whether advanced manufacturing

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:12.590
could bring a new paradigm
to the table, where

00:06:12.590 --> 00:06:15.290
US developing countries can
kind of get back in the game.

00:06:15.290 --> 00:06:18.620
So in effect, they would
take innovation leadership,

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:20.300
innovate in the
production system

00:06:20.300 --> 00:06:24.470
process and technologies, and
be able to compete better.

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:26.460
That's the essential question.

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:30.080
And as I mentioned last
week, MIT for example,

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:31.850
there are 14
manufacturing institutes

00:06:31.850 --> 00:06:33.940
that have been stood up
in the last few years.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:37.280
MIT is participating
in 9 of the 14,

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:41.090
leading one particularly
active and about three or four

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:42.620
but also participant
in the others.

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:44.630
So this is something
that's now ongoing

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:49.100
on this campus in a
pretty sizable way.

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:51.680
So that's the background
on manufacturing.

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:55.910
Now we go back to
our whole project

00:06:55.910 --> 00:06:57.470
on innovation organization.

00:06:57.470 --> 00:06:59.420
That's today's class.

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:01.490
And we're looking
at that problem

00:07:01.490 --> 00:07:06.600
of how do you innovate at
the institutional level?

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:10.110
And in particular, we're looking
at where did the US innovation

00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:12.150
system come from?

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:13.500
How did it get created?

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:15.610
How did it get put together?

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:21.630
And that's the story
that we'll weave today.

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:27.060
As a backdrop to that,
we'll start with a framework

00:07:27.060 --> 00:07:29.687
that a scholar named
David Hart put together.

00:07:29.687 --> 00:07:31.395
David teaches at George
Mason University.

00:07:31.395 --> 00:07:35.430
He teaches innovation
policy issues there.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:39.960
And he wrote this-- he got
his PhD from MIT and STS.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:45.450
He was head service in
the Office of Science

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:47.430
and Technology Policy
so he as practical

00:07:47.430 --> 00:07:50.280
as well as a lot of
academic experience.

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:53.070
Authored a big book on
energy innovation policy.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:08:00.660
David did this
book back in 1998,

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:05.330
and he essentially argued that
what's the ideology of science

00:08:05.330 --> 00:08:08.420
and technology policy?

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:12.140
If you put it into a political
economy kind of context,

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:13.730
what is the thinking process?

00:08:13.730 --> 00:08:15.900
How do you think about this?

00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:20.660
And he identified kind
of five political strains

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:24.190
in the US that, frankly--

00:08:24.190 --> 00:08:27.080
you know, I worked in the
Senate for over 15 years.

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:27.790
I saw them all.

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:28.520
They were real.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:30.280
They were all still there.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:33.640
There were all ways of
thinking about science and tech

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:37.159
policy, R&D policy that
I saw all the time.

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:39.497
So these are very
much alive and well.

00:08:39.497 --> 00:08:41.289
And David tried to put
a frame around them,

00:08:41.289 --> 00:08:47.435
and they will help guide us on
the politics of science support

00:08:47.435 --> 00:08:49.060
and technology support
in this country.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:51.160
So what are these five visions?

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:52.720
I'm going to summarize
them briefly.

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:55.280
And which of our discussion
leaders has David Hart?

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:55.780
Chloe.

00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:56.920
OK.

00:08:56.920 --> 00:09:00.840
So the first was conservatism.

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:07.400
Now, this perspective saw
no need for the state,

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:10.350
for the federal government,
to do anything other

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:12.900
than providing for
defense, including

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.200
military technological
innovation.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:21.110
Get the state out
of everything else.

00:09:21.110 --> 00:09:24.800
They've got to do defense,
but leave the rest

00:09:24.800 --> 00:09:26.420
to the private sector.

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:30.710
It's a very
non-interventionist philosophy.

00:09:30.710 --> 00:09:34.750
The budget that President
Trump just sent to Capitol Hill

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:39.800
for FY '18, largely written
by the Heritage Foundation,

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:43.940
argues exactly this
theoretical line.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:47.540
It takes-- it eliminates
ARPA-E. It takes $2 billion

00:09:47.540 --> 00:09:50.030
out of the Applied
Research Agencies

00:09:50.030 --> 00:09:53.130
and takes almost $1 billion out
of the basic research agencies

00:09:53.130 --> 00:09:54.380
at DOD.

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:57.420
It's a gigantic cutback.

00:09:57.420 --> 00:10:00.592
The theory is, let the
private sector do it.

00:10:00.592 --> 00:10:01.800
They'll do this energy stuff.

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:07.530
So this is right on us.

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:10.560
This theoretical framework
for approaching R&D support

00:10:10.560 --> 00:10:12.450
is right there.

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:14.610
One of its leading
proponents, and we'll

00:10:14.610 --> 00:10:17.640
run into him when we
talk about Alfred Loomis,

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:19.980
one of its leading proponents
in this period that David

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:21.810
is writing about in
the '20s and '30s

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:27.440
when these ideologies really got
put together, was Frank Jewett.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.720
Jewett was head of Bell Labs.

00:10:29.720 --> 00:10:32.720
And he was president of
the National Academies.

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:34.450
Had both slots.

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:37.370
And he's head of Bell Labs.

00:10:37.370 --> 00:10:40.100
He's got one of the
great basic research

00:10:40.100 --> 00:10:42.080
as well as applied
research organizations

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:45.370
in the history of the world.

00:10:45.370 --> 00:10:46.910
There is a phone monopoly.

00:10:46.910 --> 00:10:49.100
The last thing he wants
is the federal government

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:50.930
messing around in his turf.

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:55.040
Naturally, he's a proponent
of keeping the feds out,

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:58.040
except in defense and military,
which they've got to do.

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:02.540
So we'll run into to Frank
Jewett in a few minutes.

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:07.790
But this is a noninterventionist
defense-only piece.

00:11:07.790 --> 00:11:10.490
Now, on the other
side of that argument

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:13.532
is what David calls
associationalism.

00:11:13.532 --> 00:11:17.690
We would call this
public-private partnership.

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:21.590
That's the lingo that's more
or less used at this time.

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:23.900
But the meaning is
roughly the same.

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:26.600
David points out that the
first big exponent of this

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:30.080
was Herbert Hoover, who
along with Jimmy Carter,

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:32.360
was one of the
only two engineers

00:11:32.360 --> 00:11:36.390
to ever be president
of the United States.

00:11:36.390 --> 00:11:39.100
That doesn't mean there can't
be more, just as a lesson to you

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:39.600
all.

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:46.590
Hoover was an amazing engineer.

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:51.330
He was a great organizer of the
World War I war relief effort

00:11:51.330 --> 00:11:54.690
to save a staggering number
of lives after World War I.

00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:58.230
He was a highly innovative
Secretary of Commerce

00:11:58.230 --> 00:11:59.910
and made that at
the time actually

00:11:59.910 --> 00:12:03.510
one of the most important
Cabinet agencies.

00:12:03.510 --> 00:12:08.790
His vision was that unlimited
economic competition

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:15.420
curtails firms' ability
to be innovative.

00:12:15.420 --> 00:12:18.000
If you're frantic
about your competitors,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.610
you're not going to have the
energy, time, or resources

00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:25.590
to spend on longer-term,
higher-risk R&D.

00:12:25.590 --> 00:12:29.520
So there ought to be a gathering
between public and private

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:35.520
sectors that would
collaboratively undertake this.

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:40.410
So this associationalism
really occurs in the 1920s.

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:48.310
He is a great leader of NIST,
the standards organization.

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:51.010
That would be a classic
public-private collaboration,

00:12:51.010 --> 00:12:53.060
where private industry
under government auspices

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:54.810
would come together
and negotiate and work

00:12:54.810 --> 00:12:59.950
on standards for products
to enable their much more

00:12:59.950 --> 00:13:01.510
efficient production.

00:13:01.510 --> 00:13:05.620
So that would be a classic
Hoover kind of effort.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:11.260
Franklin Roosevelt adopts
this associationalist attitude

00:13:11.260 --> 00:13:12.550
when he becomes president.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:16.380
There's a lot of
public-private connectivity

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:20.140
during the Roosevelt regime.

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:22.510
So that gives us two models.

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:28.170
Now, this next model,
it's kind of disappeared.

00:13:28.170 --> 00:13:31.410
But it was a big
movement in the 1930s.

00:13:31.410 --> 00:13:42.060
The basic theory was
that cartels, monopolies,

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:47.450
collusion amongst firms
discouraged innovation.

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:49.730
You build up market control.

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:54.130
The last thing you want
is a disruptive product.

00:13:54.130 --> 00:13:58.160
And we can see this, of
course, in a sector like energy

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:00.710
even now.

00:14:00.710 --> 00:14:06.470
So the concept was reestablish
markets by legislation

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:10.160
or through example by
anti-trust laws or regulation,

00:14:10.160 --> 00:14:11.660
and you would
encourage innovation

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:14.118
to break out, because you'd be
breaking up the cartels that

00:14:14.118 --> 00:14:17.600
were limiting innovation.

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:21.040
There's so much global
competition now,

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:24.840
and the competition is so
intense that, frankly, there's

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:31.110
just not that much going on in
anti-trust practice or theory.

00:14:31.110 --> 00:14:34.230
Firms may be curtailing
innovation because

00:14:34.230 --> 00:14:36.690
of day-to-day
competitive pressures,

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:41.490
but that's not an
underlying cartel problem,

00:14:41.490 --> 00:14:43.000
because the
competition is there.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:49.820
So this one is less present
now than it was back

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:52.760
in that kind of '30s timetable.

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:55.640
A fourth is keynesianism.

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:57.890
You remember John
Maynard Keynes.

00:14:57.890 --> 00:15:01.220
Keynes develops some
crucial fundamentals

00:15:01.220 --> 00:15:03.620
of economic theory.

00:15:03.620 --> 00:15:06.380
His principle contribution
is that in periods

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:09.320
of economic downturn,
government spending

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:11.270
can step up to the
plate and substitute

00:15:11.270 --> 00:15:15.500
for the decline in private
spending and, in effect,

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:17.060
stabilize an economy.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:19.250
So we just saw this
whole theory played out

00:15:19.250 --> 00:15:21.050
in the Economic Stimulus Bill.

00:15:21.050 --> 00:15:24.770
That's what happened in
the 2009 Stimulus Bill.

00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:28.310
Massive economic stimulus.

00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:31.840
I think the economists
would say that it worked.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:36.340
It did stabilize the economy
in fairly surprisingly

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:40.360
short order, given the
depth of the threat.

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:43.810
We didn't slip into another
great recession or Great

00:15:43.810 --> 00:15:45.490
Depression.

00:15:45.490 --> 00:15:48.250
But the idea here, as applies
to science and technology,

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:51.400
is look out for the
macro-investment levels.

00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:59.820
Have a governmental role in
funding investment in research

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:03.420
and development, because
the public sector is not

00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:06.660
prone to take longer-term risks.

00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:09.060
And the government can
substitute for that.

00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:11.700
So this factor is still with us.

00:16:11.700 --> 00:16:13.890
That's why in the
first class when

00:16:13.890 --> 00:16:16.530
I had you read the National
Science Foundation Indicators

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:19.050
that told us all about
investment levels

00:16:19.050 --> 00:16:26.860
by government in R&D,
that's Keynesian thinking.

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:30.250
That's government substituting
because the private sector has

00:16:30.250 --> 00:16:32.590
difficulty undertaking
longer-term high-risk

00:16:32.590 --> 00:16:36.400
investment in research.

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:40.510
So that's another ideological
kind of element here.

00:16:40.510 --> 00:16:43.090
The fifth is a little
bit like conservatism,

00:16:43.090 --> 00:16:45.310
but it's much more far-reaching.

00:16:45.310 --> 00:16:48.100
This emerges in World
War II and the Cold War.

00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:52.230
And this doctrine says,
whatever it takes.

00:16:52.230 --> 00:16:56.640
National security is so
critical, we will do anything.

00:16:56.640 --> 00:17:00.960
The government will be
every bit as interventionist

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:06.520
as it needs to be in order
to get us national security.

00:17:06.520 --> 00:17:09.700
And that's still
very much alive.

00:17:09.700 --> 00:17:13.150
I'd say someone like Senator
John McCain, who is currently

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:17.319
the Chairman of the
Armed Services Committee,

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:19.660
Senator McCain is probably
a conservative when it comes

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:23.280
to federal R&D investment,
generally speaking,

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:28.060
but when it comes to
defense, whatever it takes.

00:17:28.060 --> 00:17:32.710
So an organization like
In-Q-Tel, which essentially

00:17:32.710 --> 00:17:35.620
buys a controlling
share in companies so

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:39.510
that the government can get
the technologies at once,

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:45.480
it's government becoming a
venture capitalist on steroids.

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:48.390
McCain is a huge
fan of that model.

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:53.400
And In-Q-Tel works in
the intelligence security

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:54.050
kind of area.

00:17:54.050 --> 00:17:57.620
So this movement is around too.

00:17:57.620 --> 00:18:02.000
And this is essentially what
Vannevar Bush puts together

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:03.800
when he creates a
connected science model--

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:05.600
we'll talk about
it a little later--

00:18:05.600 --> 00:18:07.760
during World War II.

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:10.310
So these are the ideologies.

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:12.230
I'll just summarize
them very quickly again.

00:18:12.230 --> 00:18:14.590
Conservatism.

00:18:14.590 --> 00:18:19.090
Government can do military
innovation, but that's it.

00:18:19.090 --> 00:18:19.930
Associationlism.

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:22.940
That's the public-private
partnership model.

00:18:22.940 --> 00:18:26.440
Reform liberalism, which
is stamp out cartels.

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:28.450
They limit innovation.

00:18:28.450 --> 00:18:30.670
And that's not really
a powerful movement

00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:33.130
at this point because of
international competition.

00:18:33.130 --> 00:18:36.100
Keynesianism, which is
analyze science and technology

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:39.610
based upon these
macro-investment levels

00:18:39.610 --> 00:18:42.880
by the public
sector, which serves

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:46.150
to offset a market failure
on the private sector side.

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:48.850
And then the fifth one is
this national security state.

00:18:48.850 --> 00:18:50.980
So when I was working
in the Senate,

00:18:50.980 --> 00:18:54.160
I saw all of these,
sometimes all them

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:57.340
in a single day in debate
on the Senate floor,

00:18:57.340 --> 00:19:00.400
as people would take
different perspectives

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:02.530
and different political
understandings

00:19:02.530 --> 00:19:04.690
of the role of R&D in
science and technology.

00:19:04.690 --> 00:19:07.310
So these are all still
very much with us

00:19:07.310 --> 00:19:09.550
and guide a lot of
thinking to this day.

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:11.290
The latest example,
